 FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"9427d475-e243-4131-955d-bd5c60f5c064"],

Cell["Evaluate the result.", "ItemNumbered",ExpressionUUID->"9a802983-ff43-4be8-b461-1cb33ee889b4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Modifying Built-in Definitions", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"1f9d3740-1a2b-4f41-b84a-8c31ddf2d865"],

Cell["\<\
Definitions are nothing but transformation rules for any expression. You can \
define such rules not only for functions that you add to Wolfram Language but \
also for intrinsic functions that are already built into Wolfram Language. As \
a result, you can enhance or otherwise modify the features of \
built\[Hyphen]in Wolfram Language functions. \
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"80522f81-ff32-498e-8522-adfdb6be0cc9"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["This capability is powerful, but potentially \
dangerous.",
 FontWeight->"Bold",
 FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0],
 Background->RGBColor[1, 1, 0]]], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b8941295-876a-4e22-\
96d8-4827285f9cdd"],

Cell["\<\
To avoid the possibility of changing built\[Hyphen]in functions by mistake, \
Wolfram Language \"protects\" all built\[Hyphen]in functions from \
redefinition:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ed1649e7-21b6-49f9-819f-671fa5ca19c2"],

